{"ID":270322, "Text":"<div class=\"page\"><div class=\"pageNum\"><a name=\"322\"><\/a><div class=\"prev\"><a href=\"stpjs321.html\">Prev<\/a><\/div><div class=\"next\"><a href=\"stpjs323.html\">Next<\/a><\/div>\n\t\t\t    STPJS 322<\/div>\n  <p class=\"std\">If I have sinned, I have sinned outwardly; but surely I have contemplated the things of God.<span class=\"footRef\">1<\/span><\/p>\n  <p class=\"std\">Respecting the Melchizedek Priesthood, the sectarians never professed to have it; consequently\n  they never could save any one, and would all be damned together.<span class=\"footRef\">2<\/span> There was an Episcopal priest\n  who said he had the priesthood of Aaron,<span class=\"footRef\">3<\/span> but had not the priesthood of Melchizedek:<span class=\"footRef\">4<\/span> and I bear\n  testimony that I never have found the man who claimed the Priesthood of Melchizedek. The power\n  of the Melchizedek Priesthood<span class=\"footRef\">5<\/span> is to have the power of &ldquo;endless<span class=\"footRef\">6<\/span> lives&rdquo;;<span class=\"footRef\">7<\/span> for the everlasting\n  covenant<span class=\"footRef\">8<\/span> cannot be broken.<span class=\"footRef\">9<\/span><\/p>\n  <p class=\"std\">The law was given under Aaron<span class=\"footRef\">10<\/span> for the purpose of pouring out judgments<span class=\"footRef\">11<\/span> and destructions.<\/p>\n  <div class=\"topic \">* * * <\/div>\n  <div class=\"topic \">Three Grand Orders<\/div>\n  <p class=\"std\">There are three grand orders of priesthood<span class=\"footRef\">12<\/span> referred to here.<\/p>\n  <p class=\"std\">1st. The King of Shiloam (Salem)<span class=\"footRef\">13<\/span> had power and authority over that of Abraham,<span class=\"footRef\">14<\/span> holding\n  the key and the power of endless life.<span class=\"footRef\">15<\/span> Angels desire to look into it, but they have set up too many\n  stakes.<span class=\"footRef\">16<\/span> God cursed the children of Israel<span class=\"footRef\">17<\/span> because they would not receive the last law from\n  Moses.<span class=\"footRef\">18<\/span><\/p>\n  <p class=\"std\">The sacrifice required of Abraham<span class=\"footRef\">19<\/span> in the offering up of Isaac,<span class=\"footRef\">20<\/span> shows that if a man would\n  attain to the keys of the kingdom of an endless life;<span class=\"footRef\">21<\/span> he must sacrifice all things.<span class=\"footRef\">22<\/span> When God offers\n  a blessing or knowledge to a man, and he refuses to receive it,<span class=\"footRef\">23<\/span> he will be damned. The Israelites\n  prayed that God would speak to Moses and not to them;<span class=\"footRef\">24<\/span> in consequence of which he cursed them\n  with a carnal law.<span class=\"footRef\">25<\/span><\/p>\n  <p class=\"std\">What was the power of Melchizedek?<span class=\"footRef\">26<\/span> &rsquo;Twas not the Priesthood of Aaron which administers\n  in outward ordinances,<span class=\"footRef\">27<\/span> and the offering of sacrifices.<span class=\"footRef\">28<\/span> Those holding the fulness of the\n  Melchizedek Priesthood<span class=\"footRef\">29<\/span> are kings and priests<span class=\"footRef\">30<\/span> of the Most High God,<span class=\"footRef\">31<\/span> holding the keys of power\n  and blessings.<span class=\"footRef\">32<\/span> In fact, that Priesthood is a perfect law<span class=\"footRef\">33<\/span> of theocracy, and stands as God to give\n  laws to the people, administering<span class=\"footRef\">34<\/span> endless<span class=\"footRef\">35<\/span> lives<span class=\"footRef\">36<\/span> to the sons and daughters of Adam.<span class=\"footRef\">37<\/span><\/p>\n  <p class=\"std\">Abraham says to Melchizedek, I believe all that thou hast taught me concerning the priesthood\n  and the coming of the<\/p>\n  <div class=\"footnotes\">\n    <div class=\"footnote\">1. \n      <span class=\"citation\" id=\"115938\"><a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" onclick=\"sx(this, 115938)\">&nbsp;<\/a><a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" onclick=\"gs(115938)\">D&amp;C 124:23,60<\/a><\/span>\n    <\/div>\n    <div class=\"footnote\">2. \n      <span class=\"citation\" id=\"108054\"><a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" onclick=\"sx(this, 108054)\">&nbsp;<\/a><a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" onclick=\"gs(108054)\">Matt. 15:14<\/a><\/span>\n    <\/div>\n    <div class=\"footnote\">3. \n      <span class=\"citation\" id=\"113233\"><a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" onclick=\"sx(this, 113233)\">&nbsp;<\/a><a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" onclick=\"gs(113233)\">D&amp;C 13:1<\/a><\/span>;\n      <span class=\"citation\" id=\"115412\"><a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" onclick=\"sx(this, 115412)\">&nbsp;<\/a><a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" onclick=\"gs(115412)\">D&amp;C 107:13<\/a><\/span>\n    <\/div>\n    <div class=\"footnote\">4. \n      <span class=\"citation\" id=\"115399\"><a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" onclick=\"sx(this, 115399)\">&nbsp;<\/a><a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" onclick=\"gs(115399)\">D&amp;C 107:7<\/a><\/span>;\n      <span class=\"citation\" id=\"117150\"><a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" onclick=\"sx(this, 117150)\">&nbsp;<\/a><a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" onclick=\"gs(117150)\">JS&mdash;H 1:72<\/a><\/span>\n    <\/div>\n    <div class=\"footnote\">5. \n      <span class=\"citation\" id=\"114634\"><a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" onclick=\"sx(this, 114634)\">&nbsp;<\/a><a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" onclick=\"gs(114634)\">D&amp;C 84:19<\/a><\/span>\n    <\/div>\n    <div class=\"footnote\">6. \n      <span class=\"citation\" id=\"111643\"><a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" onclick=\"sx(this, 111643)\">&nbsp;<\/a><a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" onclick=\"gs(111643)\">Mosiah 16:9<\/a><\/span>;\n      <span class=\"citation\" id=\"113292\"><a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" onclick=\"sx(this, 113292)\">&nbsp;<\/a><a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" onclick=\"gs(113292)\">D&amp;C 19:10<\/a><\/span>;\n      <span class=\"citation\" id=\"116717\"><a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" onclick